Cardiac sarcoidosis. Cardiac involvement is undeniably one of the most challenging issues in sarcoidosis. Although autopsy studies reveal heart lesions in 20 to 30% of sarcoid patients, fewer than 5% suffer from clinical disease. Cardiac sarcoidosis (CS) has a predilection for the myocardium, but the pericardium and endocardium may also be affected. CS manifestations are various and most frequently include the following: (1) aberrations of atrioventricular or intraventricular conduction, either silent or symptomatic (2) ventricular arrhythmias